cells:
I learn my commutators sets in alphabetical order, and learn each set in three discrete stages. There is approximately a two day break between each stage for a certain set of commutators; this is to allow a deeper understanding and encourage effective recall.
Stage 0: Sets I haven't started. I may already be familiar with many comms in these sets due to learning their inverses, but haven't explicity tried them as individual entities.
Stage 1: Sets I have "Learnt". This involves using blu-tack on each target on the pieces involved and executing the comm slowly to understand how it works, and exactly what it does.
Stage 2: Sets I have drilled. This involves executing each alg at full speed individually and recording the best execution time I can achieve. A lot of these are outdated, as I never return to them, so don't call me a noob Xd.
Stage 3: Sets I have time attacked. This involves timing the total execution time of one pass through of the set. Times are only recorded if I've done every single comm succesfully.
